<font color="#FF0000">MOVIES</font><br>
<tt>Tue Feb 17 20:30:28 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
I will (hopefully) be graduating from college this semester and I am taking this last semester of my undergraduate career to explore a topic that has touched my family since my father came home from his tour of duty in Vietnam.  Compelled by a beleif of &quot;my country right or wrong,&quot; my father accepted his draft notice and left for basic training in fort Lewis.  Upon his return to the US over a year later,  my father came home with malaria and  less than a hero's welcome.  Over the years, he has attempted to read the literature of Vietnam (he was in boot camp with Tim O'brien) and watch the films about the war.  The television show Tour of Duty was watched regularly, I remember.  Every time he watched or read these accounts of the war, he seemed to become a different person.  He would grow withdrawn and spend more time by himself.  My mother recalls waking him up in the middle of the night because he was screaming and thrashing in their bed.  Another side effect of the literature on the war was anger at the overwhelming anti-war(really in his mind, anti-soldier, anti-patriot) messages that many of these films convey.  Have any of you  experienced any of these same things in your dealing with vietnam?  I am meeting with several vets but I would appreciate an interactive dialogue here as well.   
